04830nam a22007215i 9783111022277DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20232023gw     fo  d z      lat d  a97831110222777 a10.1515/97831110222772doi  a(DE-B1597)634878  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 alat  agwcDE 7aREL0670802bisacsh1 aGallus, Ps.-Cyprianus, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Pseudo-Cyprian’s Heptateuchos :bBiblical Rewriting between 'narratio probabilis' and Allusive Intertextuality /cPs.-Cyprianus Gallus; Michele Cutino. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (X, 152 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCorpus Scriptorum Ecclesiasticorum Latinorum ,x1816-3882 ;v[EXTRA SERIEM]00tFrontmatter -- tIntroduction -- tTable of Contents -- tÀ la découverte d’un poème négligé : l’Exode de l’Heptateuchdichter -- tNon-Epic Classical Poetry in the Heptateuchos Poem -- tLa création de la femme (Gen. 2,18–24) dans la paraphrase biblique de l’Heptateuchos (Cypr. Gall. gen. 32–37) -- tRe-forging Balaam the Epic Way -- tBible and Intertext: An Inquiry into the Narrative Strategies in the Heptateuchos Poem -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough the Heptateuchos is possibly the most organic attempt at poetic rewriting of the Old Testament, attributed to "Cyprian the Gaul" by R. Peiper, the latest editor of the text in CSEL 23 (1891), we do not have a comprehensive analysis of this poem yet that can provide a clear grasp of the poem’s compositional logic, show which of its biblical model’s content was used, and expound the context and purpose of its versification. It is apparent that in many respects the Heptateuchos is still profoundly unknown. For this reason the UR 4377 of Catholic Theology and Religious Sciences of the University of Strasbourg, notably its ERCAM ("Équipe de recherches sur le christianisme antique et médiéval"), with its statutory members and its associate members, is engaged in the publication of a new critical edition of each of the seven books of the anonymous poem of uncertain date, the Heptateuchos, also providing an exhaustive commentary. The essays collected in this volume represent a preliminary work for the upcoming edition and commentary planned by the members of UR 4377 in Strasbourg. Above all, they show how the anonymous author was interested in safeguarding the criterion of the narratio probabilis in the poem, through probable references to Judeo-Hellenistic literature and by refining the exegetical reading of the text with references to classical and Christian poetry.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn Latin.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAltes Testament. 4aAntikes Christentum. 4aHeptateuchos. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aBible Poetry.  aHeptateuch Poet.  aLate Antiquity.  aLatin Literature.  aPs.-Cyprianus Gallus.1 aCutino, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutino, Michele, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDe Gianni, Donato, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurbetta, Luciana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLestrade, Renaud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLubian, Francesco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZimmerl-Panagl, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb0 cprintz978311101952940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311102227740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111022277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111022277/original  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_CL_PLT